“Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, so that young people in Macedonia can live freely in the European Union, because it means that we will all have a safer life,” said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, a sufficient number of parliamentarians have expressed that it will comply with the result of the vote to make it decisive.
To change the name, a two-thirds majority is required in Parliament.
