However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% recorded in the last parliamentary elections, held in 2016, in which 66% of registered persons voted.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in Macedonia's referendum on the change of name of the country, which would pave the way for membership of the European Union and NATO in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Parliament of Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavarvarkov was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents set up by the people boycotting the referendum.
“We are in favour of NATO and the EU, but we want to stick to it with our head high, not the back door,” Kavadarkov explained.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want to accept us as Macedonia, we can resort to other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Euro-Asian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev states that NATO membership will be accompanied by more than necessary investments in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
“I think the vast majority will vote in favour of it, because more than 80 per cent of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev pointed out before depositing his paper.
