John Edward: Language Competences Are Essential for World Citizens · Global Voices
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a course of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to students and parents.
The aim of independent schools is to prepare students for further and higher education, career choices and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we observe that modern languages remain a very popular and desirable matter of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we are to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages lead the classification tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68 per cent of the students who studied foreign languages obtained the A grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A qualification in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a choice class, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum from independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Competence Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons for employers’ difficulties in filling vacancies were attributed to lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Because there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such permanent competition.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person in front of the competition.
According to a survey conducted in 2013 by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% did not know how to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the French, with 15% speaking, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today's children.
Knowing different languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find important jobs.
In Scotland there is diversity between schools in the languages taught.
Some schools focus more on modern, more traditional languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the United Kingdom in the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your son's interest, he can always choose between a series of languages in independent schools, which have trained staff who specialize in this field.
Independent Scottish schools are dedicated to providing an environment of learning that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future is.
In today's global trading environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of vital importance to the country's future, and that must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communicative powers".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do this.
John Edward is director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
