North Korea declares that it will not be unilaterally disarmed "in no way" if no signs of confidence are appreciated.
The North Korean Minister for Foreign Affairs announced on Saturday to the United Nations that the ongoing sanctions were intensifying their mistrust in the United States and that, under such circumstances, the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the global organization that North Korea had taken "important steps of good will" during the previous year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test centre and committing itself to not proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not observe any response in US consonance,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and, under these circumstances, we will not initiate disarmament unilaterally in any way.”
While Ri resumed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a phase-by-phase denuclearization approach by which North Korea would be rewarded as he took action gradually, his statements seemed significant because he did not reject full unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang had already done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S. President-in-Office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the “Denuclearization of the Korean peninsula”, while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea has tried to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has reported that Pyongyang must eliminate its nuclear weapons before.
Washington has also resisted the call to relax the harsh international sanctions imposed in North Korea.
"The US insists that denuclearization must first occur and increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, as well as opposing the "war end declaration," pointed Ri.
“The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a quimera of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are intensifying our mistrust."
Ri did not refer to plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader highlighted in the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the part involved in the denuclearization issue was South Korea instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this stagnation situation."
However, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from what he held last year, when he declared to the UN General Assembly that pointing to the US territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President "Mr. Evil" Trump called Kim of "Rocket Man" on a suicide mission.
