Harvard students take a course on rest habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to fight culture, increasingly extended, to study throughout the night, stimulated by caffeine.
One academic observed that students at the world’s number one university are often unnoticed by what goes to the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sound Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of his species in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
"At the end of the talk, a girl approached me and said, "Why are you telling me now, all this, in my last year?"
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are told the basic concepts of how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of the University Health Services, said the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section there is a picture of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, dolls and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects sleeplessness, and about the importance of keeping a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Then, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily path.
“We know that the conduct of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," pointed Professor Czesler.
The culture of pride of staying awake all night still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and the growing pressure students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever greater problem.
Making sure to enjoy a sound of good quality for a long time should be a "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, tiredness and anxiety, added, even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in a mode of inanimation and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and had inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask postgraduate students to conduct a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
